n small private clubs, and  have the state government operate the supply chain and sell pot.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EMarijuana legalization supporters \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/case-for-marijuana-legalization\&quot;\u003Eargue\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E that legal marijuana will generate new tax revenues for the government without causing significant risks to public health, and help put an end to \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/7/27/5940783/prohibition-marijuana-legalization-pot-weed-racism-new-york-times\&quot;\u003Eracially skewed arrests\u003C/a\u003E in the war on drugs. Opponents \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/case-against-marijuana-legalization\&quot;\u003Esay\u003C/a\u003E legalization would give teenagers easier access to a drug that could prove harmful to their cognitive development. And with states just now starting to legalize, they&#39;re beginning to learn how the government can and can&#39;t regulate a legal marijuana market.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5319109,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/where-is-marijuana-legal&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/where-is-marijuana-legal?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5319109&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Where is marijuana legal?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EFour states have voted to fully legalize marijuana, from possession to sales. \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EWashington, DC,\u003C/span\u003E allows adults 21 and older to possess up to two ounces of marijuana,  grow up to six plants, and gift up to one ounce of pot to other adults  21 and older, but sales remain banned. And \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/12/11/7376929/marijuana-legalization-american-indians\&quot;\u003ENative American tribes\u003C/a\u003E can grow and sell marijuana, even in states where it&#39;s illegal.\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EBut marijuana remains illegal under \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-marijuana\&quot;\u003Efederal law\u003C/a\u003E, although the Obama administration \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/federal-government-deal-legal-marijuana\&quot;\u003Esaid\u003C/a\u003E it will allow state-level rules to stand without much federal interference. \u003Cbr\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana laws\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;3568240\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/OGyc43cTuA6NmrEgsyyGDFLDtkI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana laws\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/OGyc43cTuA6NmrEgsyyGDFLDtkI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EOutside of the United States, Uruguay \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/6/12/5798194/can-uruguay-kill-drug-cartels-by-legalizing-marijuana\&quot;\u003Ebecame the first country in the world\u003C/a\u003E to fully legalize marijuana in 2013. The Netherlands \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/pot-policy-5-things-to-know-about-marijuana-laws-in-the-netherlands-1.1718686\&quot;\u003Eallows\u003C/a\u003E citizens to keep and cultivate some marijuana, and police let coffee shops sell marijuana as long as they don&#39;t sell to minors or break other major rules. Spain also \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://news.yahoo.com/cannabis-clubs-barcelona-amsterdam-041321170.html\&quot;\u003Epermits\u003C/a\u003E marijuana clubs where people can use the drug, although the drug is officially illegal to sell. And according to \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/wait-marijuana-is-legal-in-north-korea\&quot;\u003Emultiple reports\u003C/a\u003E from experts, visitors, and defectors, North Korea either has no law restricting marijuana or the law goes effectively unenforced.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:7944856,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-schedule&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-schedule?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/7944856&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;How does the federal government classify marijuana?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EThe Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.justice.gov/dea/druginfo/ds.shtml\&quot;\u003Eclassifies\u003C/a\u003E marijuana as a schedule 1 drug, meaning it&#39;s perceived to have no medical value and some risk of abuse.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe classification puts marijuana in the same category as heroin and a  more restrictive category than schedule 2 drugs like cocaine and meth.  But that doesn&#39;t necessarily mean the federal government views marijuana    and heroin as equally deadly drugs, or that it considers marijuana to   be  deadlier than meth or cocaine.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cdiv class=\&quot;align-right\&quot;\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cimg src=\&quot;http://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679344/166909906.0.jpg\&quot; class=\&quot;small\&quot; alt=\&quot;marijuana\&quot;\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA marijuana plant in Spain. (AFP via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/div\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe biggest distinction between  schedule 1 and 2  substances is   whether the federal government thinks a  drug has medical  value. The  DEA  says schedule 2 substances have some  medical value and  schedule 1   substances do not, so the latter receive  more regulatory scrutiny,  even though they may not be more dangerous.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIt may be helpful to think of the scheduling system as made up of two     distinct groups: non-medical and medical. The non-medical group is   the  schedule 1 drugs, which are considered to have no medical value but    aren&#39;t numerically ranked based on abuse potential. The medical group   is  the schedule 2  to 5 drugs, which have some medical value and are    numerically ranked  based on abuse potential.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe schedule is not something the president could change alone, but  the administration, through the attorney general or secretary  of health  and human services, can begin a review process for the current  schedule.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EA review of marijuana&#39;s schedule is \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/8/7/5967239/marijuana-legalization-drug-schedule-DEA-FDA-HHS\&quot;\u003Ecurrently underway\u003C/a\u003E,  but it&#39;s unclear how long the review will take and whether it will  result in a reclassification. To date, there have been no large-scale  clinical trials on marijuana. Those kinds of studies are traditionally  required to prove marijuana has medical value to the federal government.  (Part of the problem, however, is that the federal government&#39;s  scheduling of marijuana makes it \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/9/2/6096917/medical-marijuana-legalization-colorado-research\&quot;\u003Emore difficult\u003C/a\u003E to study the drug for medical uses.)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ECongress  can also pass legislation to reschedule marijuana, which is  something  legalization advocates have been lobbying legislators to do  for a long time.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the scheduling system helps shape \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.justice.gov/dea/druginfo/ftp3.shtml\&quot;\u003Ecriminal penalties\u003C/a\u003E for illicit drug possession and sales, it&#39;s not always the final word. Penalties for marijuana are generally far more relaxed than other schedule 1 drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EStill, the classification has \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/6/11/5799916/6-ways-the-federal-government-continues-its-war-on-marijuana\&quot;\u003Eserious ramifications\u003C/a\u003E for marijuana policy, even in places where state law says pot is legal.    State-legal marijuana businesses, for instance, must function as \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/5/10/5699376/why-marijuana-shops-are-forced-to-run-like-lemonade-stands\&quot;\u003Ecash-only businesses\u003C/a\u003E largely as a result of prohibition, and they can&#39;t file for several    deductions and, as a result, their income tax rates can soar to as high    as 70 percent.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ETo learn more about marijuana&#39;s schedule, read Vox&#39;s \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/9/25/6842187/US-drug-schedule-marijuana-Justice-Department-Eric-Holder\&quot;\u003Efull explainer\u003C/a\u003E on the scheduling system.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5319929,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/case-for-marijuana-legalization&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/case-for-marijuana-legalization?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5319929&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;What&#39;s the case for marijuana legalization?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EProponents argue marijuana legalization would allow governments to redirect resources from the costly war on drugs and legitimize a revenue-generating marijuana market, without causing significant risks to public health. It would also stop \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/how-many-people-arrested-marijuana\&quot;\u003Emillions of racially skewed arrests\u003C/a\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAdvocates argue that the negative \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/health-effects-marijuana\&quot;\u003Ehealth effects\u003C/a\u003E of marijuana are minimal.\u0026nbsp;They point out that marijuana&#39;s toxicity, for example, is much lower than already-legal drugs like alcohol and tobacco.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana jars\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679436\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/oV00ieP0W7qtqLi0oZfTklDF25s=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679436/164677837.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679436/164677837.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana jars\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/oV00ieP0W7qtqLi0oZfTklDF25s=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679436/164677837.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EJars of marijuana in Colorado. (The Washington Post via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.pnas.org/content/109/40/E2657.abstract?sid=7a2a7f1f-ca77-40c4-8970-c758ca07561d\&quot;\u003Esome\u003C/a\u003E \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://journal.frontiersin.org/Journal/10.3389/fpsyt.2013.00053/full\&quot;\u003Estudies\u003C/a\u003E and \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.npr.org/blogs/health/2014/02/25/282631913/marijuana-may-hurt-the-developing-teen-brain\&quot;\u003Eexperts\u003C/a\u003E suggest a correlation between teenage marijuana use and lower IQs, legalization supporters claim the evidence doesn&#39;t prove the relationship is cause-and-effect. As \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2013/01/09/1215678110\&quot;\u003Esome research\u003C/a\u003E shows, it&#39;s possible people with lower IQs are more likely to use marijuana.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ELegalization advocates also point out that prohibition has failed to reduce marijuana use. The war on drugs originally intended to take down illegal drug supplies, increase prices as a result, and make the drug unaffordable to users. Those goals failed: the White House&#39;s Office of National Drug Control Policy \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.whitehouse.gov/ondcp/price-and-purity\&quot;\u003Efound\u003C/a\u003E marijuana prices dropped and stabilized starting after early 1990s, and\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.monitoringthefuture.org\&quot;\u003Eseveral\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.samhsa.gov/data/NSDUH/2012SummNatFindDetTables/NationalFindings/NSDUHresults2012.htm#fig2.10\&quot;\u003Esurveys\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E show\u003C/span\u003E \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-legalization-more-marijuana-use\&quot;\u003Emarijuana use\u003C/a\u003E rose and stabilized among youth in the same time period.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EMeanwhile, drug prohibition has created a lucrative black market for drug cartels. Studies from the \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://imco.org.mx/images/pdf/reporte-tecnico-legalizacion-marihuana.pdf\&quot;\u003EMexican Institute of Competitiveness\u003C/a\u003E and the \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.rand.org/pubs/occasional_papers/OP325.html\&quot;\u003ERAND Corporation\u003C/a\u003E suggest marijuana makes up roughly 20 to 30 percent of drug cartels&#39; revenue. If pot were legalized, drug cartels would most likely lose much of that revenue as sales transition to a legal market.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;war on drugs protest\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;646846\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/y6nbhQWkwMW31hXRRXiiAYBS28g=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4691605/170749658.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4691605/170749658.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;war on drugs protest\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/y6nbhQWkwMW31hXRRXiiAYBS28g=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4691605/170749658.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA demonstrator protests the war on drugs and its disproportionate impact on black communities. (Saul Loeb / AFP via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EMarijuana prohibition also led to \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/how-many-people-arrested-marijuana\&quot;\u003Emillions of arrests\u003C/a\u003E over the last decade that disproportionally affected minorities, according to the American Civil Liberties Union. These arrests don&#39;t necessarily lead to prison time: estimates put only \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://books.google.com/books?id=mO0CTJCZsiQC\u0026q=6+million#v=onepage\u0026q=40%2C000\u0026f=false\&quot;\u003E40,000 people\u003C/a\u003E in state and federal prisons for marijuana. But marijuana advocates see even the threat of arrest as too much for what they call a relatively harmless substance.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ETaken together, legalization supporters say it&#39;s time to turn marijuana into a legitimate market for governments and businesses. Through legalization, proponents argue, the marijuana market could fuel economic growth and \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/tax-revenue-marijuana-legalization\&quot;\u003Eincreased tax revenues\u003C/a\u003E, instead of powerful drug cartels and more arrests.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5320355,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/case-against-marijuana-legalization&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/case-against-marijuana-legalization?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5320355&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;What&#39;s the case against marijuana legalization?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EOpponents of legalized marijuana argue relaxed drug laws will increase marijuana use, which could be particularly damaging for children and teenagers.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cdiv class=\&quot;align-right\&quot;\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;John Hickenlooper\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679464\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/iyiAnsp31tq7_-aOnDG8NGE3Mgg=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679464/165376333.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679464/165376333.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;John Hickenlooper\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/iyiAnsp31tq7_-aOnDG8NGE3Mgg=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679464/165376333.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EColorado Governor John Hickenlooper (D) opposed the ballot measure that legalized marijuana. (Doug Pensinger / Getty Images News)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/div\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.pnas.org/content/109/40/E2657.abstract?sid=7a2a7f1f-ca77-40c4-8970-c758ca07561d\&quot; style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot;\u003ESome\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://journal.frontiersin.org/Journal/10.3389/fpsyt.2013.00053/full\&quot; style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot;\u003Estudies\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E and \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.npr.org/blogs/health/2014/02/25/282631913/marijuana-may-hurt-the-developing-teen-brain\&quot; style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot;\u003Eexperts\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E suggest teenage marijuana use correlates with worse brain development and lower IQs. There&#39;s also concern that marijuana could act as a gateway to other drugs, like heroin and cocaine, but the research on this point \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-gateway-drug\&quot;\u003Edisputes that claim\u003C/a\u003E. \u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EColorado Governor John Hickenlooper (D) opposed marijuana legalization when it was on the ballot in his state, arguing that doing so would de-stigmatize drug use. \&quot;Amendment 64 has the potential to increase the number of children using drugs and would detract from efforts to make Colorado the healthiest state in the nation,\&quot; he said in a\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/12/gov-john-hickenlooper-opp_n_1879248.html\&quot;\u003E2012 statement\u003C/a\u003E announcing his opposition. \&quot;It sends the wrong message to kids that drugs are OK.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/9/23/6218695/case-against-pot-legalization-big-marijuana\&quot;\u003EThe big concern\u003C/a\u003E is that letting for-profit businesses market and sell marijuana encourages them to sell to minors and drug abusers, who tend to make up the largest demand for marijuana. This is similar to what&#39;s happened in the alcohol and tobacco industries, where companies make a bulk of their profits from people who use their drugs of choice quite frequently — often to the point of abuse.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIn Colorado, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.colorado.gov/cs/Satellite?blobcol=urldata\u0026blobheadername1=Content-Disposition\u0026blobheadername2=Content-Type\u0026blobheadervalue1=inline%3B+filename%3D%22Market+Size+and+Demand+Study%2C+July+9%2C+2014.pdf%22\u0026blobheadervalue2=application%2Fpdf\u0026blobkey=id\u0026blobtable=MungoBlobs\u0026blobwhere=1252008574534\u0026ssbinary=true\&quot;\u003Eone study\u003C/a\u003E of the state&#39;s pot market, conducted by the Marijuana Policy Group for  the Colorado Department of Revenue, found the top 29.9 percent heaviest  pot users in Colorado made up 87.1 percent of demand for the drug. For  the marijuana industry, that makes the heaviest users the most lucrative  customers.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana demand\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;775718\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/y4rd4KHN543d2MzyDJilsVZpYto=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/775718/marijuana_demand.0.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/775718/marijuana_demand.0.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana demand\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/y4rd4KHN543d2MzyDJilsVZpYto=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/775718/marijuana_demand.0.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EMark Kleiman, one of the leading drug policy experts in the country, supports a tightly regulated form of legalization. His concern with the current model of legalization is that it will lead to the widespread commercialization of pot — and for-profit businesses will take advantage of the situation. \&quot;Their best customers are the problem users,\&quot; Kleiman said. \&quot;They are   an industry with a set of objectives that flatly contradicts public   interest.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003ESome oppose legalization and instead \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.ktxs.com/news/rick-perry-supports-decriminalization-of-marijuana/24984908\&quot; style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot;\u003Eargue\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E for smaller actions. \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EFor these incrementalists,\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-marijuana-decriminalization\&quot;\u003Emarijuana decriminalization\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E would keep a legal stigma against marijuana and remove harsh criminal penalties. Portugal, for instance, decriminalized all drugs, including marijuana, instead of pursuing all-out legalization. \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.cato.org/publications/white-paper/drug-decriminalization-portugal-lessons-creating-fair-successful-drug-policies\&quot; style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot;\u003EA 2009 Cato Institute report\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E found drug-related deaths dropped as a result, and more drug addicts sought rehabilitation services because the  policy removed the fear of arrest.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EOthers also support \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-medical-marijuana\&quot;\u003Emedical marijuana\u003C/a\u003E but not full marijuana legalization. Washington Governor Jay Inslee (D) took this stance as a gubernatorial candidate, when his state was debating marijuana legalization.\u0026nbsp;\&quot;I&#39;m in favor of making sure people have access to medical marijuana.… I&#39;m not comfortable with voting for [the legalization] initiative,\&quot; Inslee\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://blog.seattlepi.com/seattlepolitics/2012/03/23/inslee-no-to-marijuana-legalization-initiative/\&quot;\u003Etold \u003C/a\u003Ea Seattle radio station in 2012.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5378075,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/wait-marijuana-is-legal-in-north-korea&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/wait-marijuana-is-legal-in-north-korea?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5378075&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Wait, marijuana is legal in North Korea?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EIt&#39;s unclear if marijuana is legal in North Korea, but \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/08/marijuana-in-north-korea_n_4067341.html\&quot;\u003Ethe Huffington Post\u003C/a\u003E found there&#39;s either no law against marijuana or the law is largely unenforced.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFreelance writer \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.thebohemianblog.com/2013/09/on-smoking-weed-in-north-korea.html\&quot;\u003EDarmon Richter\u003C/a\u003E documented his experiences with marijuana in North Korea. Richter was apparently able to buy a bag of the drug for \u003Cspan class=\&quot;fullpost\&quot;\u003Eabout £0.50 (about 84 cents, which is very cheap) in an open market.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;darmon richter marijuana bag\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;635510\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/V_xvaebRu11crY-P0Wk_l2xD7oA=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4303701/darmon_richter_marijuana_bag.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/assets/4303701/darmon_richter_marijuana_bag.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;darmon richter marijuana bag\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/V_xvaebRu11crY-P0Wk_l2xD7oA=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4303701/darmon_richter_marijuana_bag.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA bag of marijuana, purchased in North Korea. (\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.thebohemianblog.com/2013/09/on-smoking-weed-in-north-korea.html\&quot;\u003EDarmon Richter\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ERichter claimed he was also able to smoke marijuana joints in public. No one — not even a coughing waitress — complained.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ERichter&#39;s experience has been backed by other reports: citing North Korean sources, \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vice.com/read/north-korea-is-stoned-all-the-time-which-explains-a-lot\&quot;\u003EVice News\u003C/a\u003E claimed \&quot;the drug is especially popular among the lower classes of North Korean  society. After a day of hard manual labor, it is common for North Korean  workers to smoke marijuana as a way to relax and soothe tight or sore  muscles.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIt&#39;s not just the lower classes, either. A 2010 report from \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://english.nkradio.org/news/286\&quot;\u003EOpen Radio for North Korea\u003C/a\u003E found Kim Jong Un&#39;s regime doesn&#39;t consider marijuana — or opium, for that matter — to be an illicit drug.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5318829,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-marijuana-decriminalization&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-marijuana-decriminalization?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5318829&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;What is marijuana decriminalization?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EMarijuana decriminalization eliminates criminal penalties, such as extended prison time, for possession of a limited amount of the drug.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EBut this doesn&#39;t mean that possessing pot is legal in places where it&#39;s  decriminalized. Those caught possessing or selling an amount within  decriminalized limits are still fined, usually a few hundred dollars.\u0026nbsp;\u003Cspan\u003EStates with stricter decriminalization laws also attach some jail time, particularly to trafficking.\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E\u003C/span\u003E And those caught with large amounts of marijuana, even in places where  the drug is decriminalized, still face criminal penalties.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana grow\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679354\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/eCZtrPzOEAN42BPU17-eVXu_S-4=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679354/149251752.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679354/149251752.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana grow\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/eCZtrPzOEAN42BPU17-eVXu_S-4=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679354/149251752.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EThis kind of marijuana grow would still get someone in trouble in states with decriminalization. (David McNew / Getty Images News)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EDecriminalization laws vary from \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.mpp.org/states/\&quot;\u003Estate to state\u003C/a\u003E, but they typically apply to anyone possessing a small amount of marijuana. Whether a small amount means 10 or 100 grams depends on the state&#39;s laws. (In comparison, a marijuana joint weighs about half a gram.)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EMarijuana is decriminalized in 19 states, and in three of those states and the District of Columbia, it&#39;s legalized.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana laws\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;3568240\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/OGyc43cTuA6NmrEgsyyGDFLDtkI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana laws\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/OGyc43cTuA6NmrEgsyyGDFLDtkI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ESupporters of decriminalization often point to Portugal as evidence of the policy&#39;s success. \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.cato.org/publications/white-paper/drug-decriminalization-portugal-lessons-creating-fair-successful-drug-policies\&quot;\u003EA 2009 Cato Institute report\u003C/a\u003E found drug-related deaths dropped after Portugal decriminalized all drugs, and more drug addicts sought rehabilitation services because the policy removed the fear of arrest. But \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-legalization-more-marijuana-use\&quot;\u003Edrug use\u003C/a\u003E increased among adults aged 20 to 24.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5318851,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-medical-marijuana&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-medical-marijuana?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5318851&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;What is medical marijuana?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EMedical marijuana is just marijuana except, as the name implies, it&#39;s used for medical instead of recreational purposes.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cdiv class=\&quot;align-right\&quot;\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;medical marijuana\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679362\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/7PKRLcJI8un_j3a787WFrj7yNu4=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679362/99037642.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679362/99037642.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;medical marijuana\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/7PKRLcJI8un_j3a787WFrj7yNu4=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679362/99037642.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA manager at a medical marijuana dispensary holds up a bottle of the drug. (Kevork Djansezian / Getty Images News)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/div\u003E\r\n\u003Cp id=\&quot;docs-internal-guid-8af92281-050e-dfeb-df29-b701b5302b09\&quot; dir=\&quot;ltr\&quot;\u003ESome studies and anecdotal evidence suggest marijuana can be used for various medical problems, including \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.cmaj.ca/content/182/14/E694.abstract\&quot;\u003Epain\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://medicalmarijuana.procon.org/sourcefiles/IOM_Report.pdf\&quot;\u003Enausea and loss of appetite\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24614667%20\&quot;\u003EParkinson&#39;s disease\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23648372\&quot;\u003Einflammatory bowel disease\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://communications.med.nyu.edu/media-relations/news/brain-imaging-study-links-cannabinoid-receptors-post-traumatic-stress-disorder\&quot;\u003EPTSD\u003C/a\u003E (post-traumatic stress disorder), \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.epilepsy.com/newsfeeds/press_release/1002788%20\&quot;\u003Eepilepsy\u003C/a\u003E, and \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/276046.php\&quot;\u003Emultiple sclerosis\u003C/a\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp dir=\&quot;ltr\&quot;\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/8/25/6065383/medical-marijuana-legalization-linked-to-less-prescription-painkiller\&quot;\u003EOne study\u003C/a\u003E suggested the legalization of medical marijuana could even lead to fewer prescription painkiller deaths, since marijuana can relieve pain without the risks of overdose and dependency that come with opioid-based pharmaceuticals. In states that legalized marijuana for medical purposes, there were nearly 25 percent fewer deaths from prescription painkillers than expected, based on historical rates and trends in places that don&#39;t allow medicinal pot.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp dir=\&quot;ltr\&quot;\u003EBut the federal government \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/9/25/6842187/US-drug-schedule-marijuana-Justice-Department-Eric-Holder\&quot;\u003Edoesn&#39;t recognize\u003C/a\u003E this medical potential, largely because the studies have been small so far, and there have been no large-scale clinical trials proving pot&#39;s medicinal value.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp dir=\&quot;ltr\&quot;\u003EIt&#39;s long been difficult to conduct thorough studies on the medical uses of marijuana, because of \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-marijuana\&quot;\u003Ethe drug&#39;s prohibition\u003C/a\u003E and the need for approval from a federal government that&#39;s more interested in studying marijuana&#39;s potential for abuse than its benefits. This creates a bit of a Catch-22: there needs to be a certain level of scientific research proving  marijuana has medical value, but the federal government&#39;s restrictions  make it difficult to conduct that research.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp dir=\&quot;ltr\&quot;\u003EStill, some experts now claim it&#39;s time to seriously look at marijuana&#39;s medical benefits. Dr. Sanjay Gupta of CNN in 2013 \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/08/health/gupta-changed-mind-marijuana/index.html\&quot;\u003Ecited\u003C/a\u003E a loud chorus of legitimate patients when he announced his shift in position to support for medical marijuana. For marijuana advocates, Gupta&#39;s \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/10/sanjay-gupta-medical-marijuana-legalization_n_4932277.html\&quot;\u003Eheadline\u003C/a\u003E-\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://blog.sfgate.com/smellthetruth/2014/03/06/sanjay-gupta-doubles-down-on-medical-marijuana-with-new-weed-2-documentary/\&quot;\u003Egrabbing\u003C/a\u003E \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.cbsnews.com/news/sanjay-gupta-backs-medical-marijuana-apologizes-for-previous-views/\&quot;\u003Esupport\u003C/a\u003E represented a major shift in the medical world&#39;s attitude toward the drug.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp dir=\&quot;ltr\&quot;\u003ESeveral states have already legalized medical marijuana, although the drug remains illegal for all purposes at the federal level. States&#39; laws can significantly differ: some, like California, allow medical marijuana dispensaries and home cultivation; others, such as Alaska, only allow home cultivation; and a few, such as Delaware, allow dispensaries but not home cultivation.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp dir=\&quot;ltr\&quot;\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana laws\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;3568240\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/OGyc43cTuA6NmrEgsyyGDFLDtkI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana laws\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/OGyc43cTuA6NmrEgsyyGDFLDtkI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568240/marijuana_laws.0.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5427511,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/where-are-the-next-rounds-of-marijuana-legalization-efforts&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/where-are-the-next-rounds-of-marijuana-legalization-efforts?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5427511&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Which states could legalize marijuana next?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EWith\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/-popular-opinion-changing-marijuana-legalization\&quot;\u003Epublic support\u003C/a\u003E climbing for marijuana legalization, advocates are gearing up for several legalization campaigns in the next few years.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;which states could legalize marijuana next\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;3568964\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/m8iZFCP_2YdoB32GqhB23dPkdDI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568964/which_states_could_legalize_marijuana_next.0.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568964/which_states_could_legalize_marijuana_next.0.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;which states could legalize marijuana next\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/m8iZFCP_2YdoB32GqhB23dPkdDI=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/3568964/which_states_could_legalize_marijuana_next.0.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EBy 2017, the Marijuana Policy Project, a coalition of marijuana legalization advocates, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.mpp.org/our-work/\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;\u003Eaims to pass\u003C/a\u003E several more state-level laws that would regulate marijuana in the same  way as alcohol. Some campaigns will target ballot initiatives — in  Arizona  (2016), California (2016), Maine (2016), Massachusetts (2016),  and Nevada (2016). Others will go through state legislatures, where  supporters will lobby for  legalization in Hawaii, Maryland, New  Hampshire, Rhode Island, and  Vermont.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\&quot;It&#39;s an uphill battle,\&quot; said Marijuana Policy Project spokesperson Mason Tvert, \&quot;but we see support growing at the state and  federal level.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5320553,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/-popular-opinion-changing-marijuana-legalization&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/-popular-opinion-changing-marijuana-legalization?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5320553&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;How is public opinion changing on marijuana legalization?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EMarijuana legalization has quickly become more popular in the United States.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAccording to \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.gallup.com/poll/179195/majority-continues-support-pot-legalization.aspx\&quot;\u003Edecades of surveys\u003C/a\u003E from Gallup, support for legalization rose from 12 percent in 1970 to 31 percent in 2000 to 51 percent in 2014. \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://civicscience.com/what-the-mainstreaming-of-marijuana-means-to-marketers/\&quot;\u003EAnother poll\u003C/a\u003E from Civic Science found similar levels of support in 2014.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Gallup marijuana legalization\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;2435724\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/283yz1JpOnHtrMMVyUuI5w_x8RE=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2435724/Gallup_marijuana_legalization.0.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2435724/Gallup_marijuana_legalization.0.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Gallup marijuana legalization\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/283yz1JpOnHtrMMVyUuI5w_x8RE=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2435724/Gallup_marijuana_legalization.0.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe Pew Research Center \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.pewsocialtrends.org/2014/03/07/millennials-in-adulthood/sdt-next-america-03-07-2014-2-11/\&quot;\u003Efound\u003C/a\u003E support varies from generation to generation. More than two-thirds of millennials back legalizing marijuana, but support is lower among older groups.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ccenter\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana support generational divide\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;632758\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/pqkB-2-23GrGSNCxZy8rh5AFdDk=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203263/marijuana_generational_divide.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203263/marijuana_generational_divide.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana support generational divide\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/pqkB-2-23GrGSNCxZy8rh5AFdDk=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203263/marijuana_generational_divide.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/center\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5322689,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/how-many-people-arrested-marijuana&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/how-many-people-arrested-marijuana?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5322689&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;How many people get arrested for marijuana-related offenses?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EThere were about 784,000 arrests for marijuana possession in 2010, the latest year of data analyzed by \u003Ca href=\&quot;https://www.aclu.org/criminal-law-reform/new-aclu-report-finds-overwhelming-racial-bias-marijuana-arrests\&quot;\u003Ea report\u003C/a\u003E from the American Civil Liberties Union. Not all of those arrests led to prison time. Estimates put only \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://books.google.com/books?id=mO0CTJCZsiQC\u0026q=6+million#v=onepage\u0026q=40%2C000\u0026f=false\&quot;\u003E40,000 people\u003C/a\u003E in state and federal prisons for marijuana.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ccenter\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203569/marijuana_arrests_1995-2010.png\&quot;\u003E\u003Cimg src=\&quot;http://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203569/marijuana_arrests_1995-2010_medium.png\&quot; class=\&quot;photo\&quot; alt=\&quot;Marijuana_arrests_1995-2010_medium\&quot;\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003E(\u003Ca href=\&quot;https://www.aclu.org/criminal-law-reform/new-aclu-report-finds-overwhelming-racial-bias-marijuana-arrests\&quot;\u003EAmerican Civil Liberties Union\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/center\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe ACLU also found the share of marijuana arrests rose compared to all drug arrests between 1995 and 2010. In 2010, about 784,000 out of 1.7 million drug arrests were for marijuana possession.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ccenter\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203593/marijuana_arrests_share_1995-2010.png\&quot;\u003E\u003Cimg src=\&quot;http://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203593/marijuana_arrests_share_1995-2010_medium.png\&quot; class=\&quot;photo\&quot; alt=\&quot;Marijuana_arrests_share_1995-2010_medium\&quot;\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003E(\u003Ca href=\&quot;https://www.aclu.org/criminal-law-reform/new-aclu-report-finds-overwhelming-racial-bias-marijuana-arrests\&quot;\u003EAmerican Civil Liberties Union\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/center\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAmong those arrested, the ACLU found giant racial disparities. Black and white Americans use marijuana at \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/7/27/5940783/prohibition-marijuana-legalization-pot-weed-racism-new-york-times\&quot;\u003Esimilar rates\u003C/a\u003E. But black Americans were 3.73 times more likely to be arrested than white Americans for marijuana possession, with the black arrest rate at 716 per 100,000 and the white arrest rate at 192 per 100,000 in 2010.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ccenter\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203657/black_v_white_marijuana_possession_arrest.png\&quot;\u003E\u003Cimg src=\&quot;http://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/assets/4203657/black_v_white_marijuana_possession_arrest_medium.png\&quot; class=\&quot;photo\&quot; alt=\&quot;Black_v_white_marijuana_possession_arrest_medium\&quot;\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003E(\u003Ca href=\&quot;https://www.aclu.org/criminal-law-reform/new-aclu-report-finds-overwhelming-racial-bias-marijuana-arrests\&quot;\u003EAmerican Civil Liberties Union\u003C/a\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/center\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5322923,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/health-effects-marijuana&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/health-effects-marijuana?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5322923&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;What are the health effects of marijuana use?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EMarijuana is\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2015/2/25/8104917/drug-dangers-marijuana-alcohol\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;\u003Erelatively safe\u003C/a\u003E compared to other drugs, including alcohol. But studies show marijuana could carry some health risks, particularly for children, teenagers, and younger adults.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\&quot;The main risk of cannabis is losing control of your cannabis  intake,\&quot; Mark Kleiman, a drug policy expert at UCLA, said. \&quot;That&#39;s going  to have consequences in terms of the amount of time you spend not fully  functional. When that&#39;s hours per day times years, that&#39;s bad.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ECaulkins of Carnegie Mellon University put it another way: \&quot;At some  level, we know that spending more than half of your waking hours  intoxicated for years and years on end is not increasing the likelihood  that you&#39;ll win a Pulitzer Prize or discover the cure for cancer.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E \u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;teen marijuana joint\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;666780\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/W-8E-TrTO_M6oR9ho6noJSX4aZQ=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/666780/175231438.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/666780/175231438.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;teen marijuana joint\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/W-8E-TrTO_M6oR9ho6noJSX4aZQ=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/666780/175231438.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n \u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA teen holds a joint. (Universal Images Group via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThese problems are compounded by the perception that pot is harmless:  since many marijuana users believe what they&#39;re doing won&#39;t hurt them,  they feel much more comfortable falling into a habit of constantly using  the drug.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/9/24/6538227/marijuana-pot-adolescent-teen-use-research-studies\&quot;\u003EA lot of research\u003C/a\u003E has also linked adolescent marijuana use with a range of negative consequences,\u003Cb\u003E \u003C/b\u003Eincluding  cognitive deficiencies and worse educational outcomes. While it&#39;s not  clear whether marijuana&#39;s role with these outcomes is cause-and-effect,  experts generally agree that people younger than their mid-20s should  avoid pot.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe research on other health effects of marijuana is inconclusive. \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.thelancet.com/pb/assets/raw/Lancet/pdfs/14TLP0454_Di%20Forti.pdf\&quot;\u003EOne study\u003C/a\u003E linked the use of potent marijuana to psychotic disorders, but \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.schres-journal.com/article/S0920-9964%2813%2900610-5/abstract\&quot;\u003Eother\u003C/a\u003E \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.kcl.ac.uk/ioppn/news/records/2014/June/Schizophrenia-and-cannabis-use-may-share-common-genes.aspx\&quot;\u003Estudies\u003C/a\u003E suggest people with psychotic disorders may be predisposed to pot use.  Research on whether smoked marijuana causes lung disease or cancer has  yielded \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/pdq/cam/cannabis/healthprofessional/page5\&quot;\u003Econflicting results\u003C/a\u003E, with studies that control for tobacco smoking finding no significant effect from marijuana on lung cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EMeanwhile, the research and anecdotal evidence suggest marijuana could be used to treat \u003C/span\u003Eseveral medical problems\u003Cspan\u003E, such as \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.cmaj.ca/content/182/14/E694.abstract\&quot;\u003Epain\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://medicalmarijuana.procon.org/sourcefiles/IOM_Report.pdf\&quot;\u003Enausea and loss of appetite\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24614667\&quot;\u003EParkinson&#39;s disease\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23648372\&quot;\u003Einflammatory bowel disease\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://communications.med.nyu.edu/media-relations/news/brain-imaging-study-links-cannabinoid-receptors-post-traumatic-stress-disorder\&quot;\u003EPTSD\u003C/a\u003E (post-traumatic stress disorder), and \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.epilepsy.com/newsfeeds/press_release/1002788\&quot;\u003Eepilepsy\u003C/a\u003E. These findings are why many advocates support the legalization of \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-medical-marijuana\&quot;\u003Emedical marijuana\u003C/a\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5324183,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/federal-government-deal-legal-marijuana&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/federal-government-deal-legal-marijuana?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5324183&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;How does the federal government deal with legal marijuana?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EThe federal government does not interfere with state laws that legalize marijuana as long as states enforce certain standards, like a ban on sales to minors.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cdiv class=\&quot;align-right\&quot;\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Eric Holder\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679730\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0y7SehVfvIm4ciK715IKRzRSU8o=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679730/147369910.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679730/147369910.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Eric Holder\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0y7SehVfvIm4ciK715IKRzRSU8o=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679730/147369910.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EUS Attorney General Eric Holder issued the guidances allowing states&#39; relaxed marijuana laws. (Chris Graythen / Getty Images News)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003C/div\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe Obama administration in 2013\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/obama-administration-will-not-preempt-state-marijuana-laws--for-now/2013/08/29/b725bfd8-10bd-11e3-8cdd-bcdc09410972_story.html\&quot;\u003E filed a guidance\u003C/a\u003E asking prosecutors and regulators to avoid coming down on individual  marijuana users and businesses in states where marijuana is legal. The guidance, however, maintained exceptions that allow prosecutors to crack down on instances in which legal marijuana is sold to minors, is grown on public land, falls into the hands of drug cartels, or spreads to states where the drug remains illegal.\u0026nbsp;\u003Cspan\u003EThe guidance does not grant legal immunity, but it tells prosecutors and regulators to prioritize other issues.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe Obama administration also showed its tolerance for marijuana legalization by \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/15/us/us-issues-marijuana-guidelines-for-banks.html?_r=0\&quot;\u003Etrying to assure banks\u003C/a\u003E that they will not be punished if they hold cash from state-legal marijuana businesses. But the guidance also required banks to heavily scrutinize pot shops and producers — to the point that most banks deemed the guidance unrealistic and, as a result, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/8/12/5994845/more-than-100-banks-working-with-marijuana-businesses\&quot;\u003Estill don&#39;t loan to or open accounts\u003C/a\u003E for the marijuana industry, forcing many pot shops and producers to function as \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/5/10/5699376/why-marijuana-shops-are-forced-to-run-like-lemonade-stands\&quot;\u003Ecash-only businesses\u003C/a\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFederal laws have interfered in \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/6/11/5799916/6-ways-the-federal-government-continues-its-war-on-marijuana\&quot;\u003Eother ways\u003C/a\u003E with states&#39; marijuana laws. State-legal marijuana businesses, for instance,\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.npr.org/2013/04/02/176042513/for-legal-pot-sellers-a-big-tax-problem\&quot;\u003Ecan&#39;t file\u003C/a\u003E for several  deductions and, as a result, their income tax rates can soar to as high  as 70 percent. The US Bureau of Reclamation also \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2014/05/20/227970/no-irrigation-water-for-marijuana.html\&quot;\u003Edoesn&#39;t allow\u003C/a\u003E marijuana producers to use federal waterways to grow the plant, which forces state-legal growers to look for other sources of water.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EDespite the problems, President Barack Obama \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/president-obama-marijuana-legalization\&quot;\u003Erecently stated\u003C/a\u003E that it&#39;s important to allow legalization experiments to continue.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5324243,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/president-obama-marijuana-legalization&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/president-obama-marijuana-legalization?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5324243&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;What is President Barack Obama’s stance on marijuana legalization?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EPresident Barack Obama opposes marijuana legalization, but he\u003Ci\u003E \u003C/i\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2014/01/27/140127fa_fact_remnick?currentPage=all\&quot;\u003Etold The New Yorker\u003C/a\u003E that states&#39; marijuana legalization plans must be allowed to continue. The president explained that he views marijuana as no more dangerous than alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;president obama\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679780\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/B0DcOnsEH2wfgcEydSIFg3KXWtw=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679780/143545778.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679780/143545778.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;president obama\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/B0DcOnsEH2wfgcEydSIFg3KXWtw=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679780/143545778.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EPresident Barack Obama views marijuana as no more dangerous than alcohol. (Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe federal government&#39;s\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/federal-government-deal-legal-marijuana#E5758886\&quot;\u003Erelaxed enforcement\u003C/a\u003E of marijuana laws reflects the president&#39;s cautious take on marijuana legalization. The administration in multiple guidances told prosecutors and regulators to prioritize other issues, as long as states enforce certain standards, such as a ban on marijuana sales to children.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAt the same time, Vice President Joe Biden \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://time.com/5330/marijuana-legalization-joe-biden-pot/\&quot;\u003Ecautioned\u003C/a\u003E that the Obama administration will not pursue marijuana legalization at the federal level. \&quot;I think the idea of focusing significant resources on interdicting or convicting people for smoking marijuana is a waste of our resources,\&quot; Biden told Time. \&quot;That&#39;s different than [legalization]. Our policy for our administration is still not legalization.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5324277,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/states-regulate-legal-marijuana&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/states-regulate-legal-marijuana?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5324277&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;How do states regulate legal marijuana?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EStates where marijuana is legal tax and regulate the drug much like alcohol, but specific rules vary from state to state.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Colorado marijuana\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679784\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/84qg3W5X3ojT1ZV_7g5-P4ZsvSk=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679784/459976707.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679784/459976707.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Colorado marijuana\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn1.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/84qg3W5X3ojT1ZV_7g5-P4ZsvSk=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679784/459976707.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EContainers of marijuana in Colorado. (Kathryn Scott Osler / Denver Post via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EBoth \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.denverpost.com/marijuana/ci_24823785/colorado-marijuana-guide-64-answers-commonly-asked-questions\&quot;\u003EColorado\u003C/a\u003E and \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://lcb.wa.gov/marijuana/faqs_i-502\&quot;\u003EWashington\u003C/a\u003E, for instance, tax marijuana, allow only adults 21 and older to possess the drug, and prohibit driving while intoxicated, just like alcohol. But Colorado allows each household to grow up to six recreational  marijuana plants, while Washington bans  home-growing marijuana for recreational use.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ERules on \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-medical-marijuana\&quot;\u003Emedical marijuana\u003C/a\u003E also differ from state to state. \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/25/us/25pot.html?gwh=9A03C637B1F044998CC40A9662AB5187\u0026gwt=pay\&quot;\u003EColorado\u003C/a\u003E, for example, doesn&#39;t allow medical marijuana for PTSD (post-traumatic stress disorder) patients; \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/25/us/25pot.html?gwh=9A03C637B1F044998CC40A9662AB5187\u0026gwt=pay\&quot;\u003ENew Mexico\u003C/a\u003E and \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.wzzm13.com/story/news/health/2014/03/24/veterans-with-ptsd-can-now-use-to-medical-marijuana/6835877/\&quot;\u003EMichigan\u003C/a\u003E do. Similar differences play out on a state-by-state basis depending on the medical problem and the ease of access to medical marijuana cards.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFor more information, advocacy group NORML \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://norml.org/states\&quot;\u003Emaintains a comprehensive database\u003C/a\u003E of state-by-state laws.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5324325,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-gateway-drug&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-gateway-drug?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5324325&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Is marijuana a gateway drug?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EThe gateway drug theory claims that the relationship between marijuana and harder drugs is cause-and-effect: marijuana use leads to harder drug use.\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E But while there is some evidence that marijuana users are more likely to use harder drugs, most recent research suggests it&#39;s not a causal relationship.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana jars\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679800\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/g6asf_fl8bBvKWWPDfgY5605l0g=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679800/459977259_1_.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679800/459977259_1_.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana jars\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/g6asf_fl8bBvKWWPDfgY5605l0g=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679800/459977259_1_.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003ECould smoking Green Crack lead to using actual crack? (Seth McConnell / Denver Post via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.nap.edu/catalog.php?record_id=6376\&quot;\u003Ea big report\u003C/a\u003E issued by the federal government in 1999, the highly prestigious Institute of Medicine found there&#39;s no evidence that marijuana is a gateway drug.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EMore recently, \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca style=\&quot;background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.5;\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.rand.org/pubs/research_briefs/RB6010/index1.html\&quot;\u003Ean analysis\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E from RAND&#39;s Drug Policy Research Center argues the gateway drug theory could represent a misreading of the data. Habitual drug users, for example, could be more likely to use a variety of drugs, which could explain the correlation between marijuana and other drug use. Furthermore, drug users only try marijuana first because it is more accessible than harder drugs; if cocaine and heroin were equally accessible, drug users could be just as likely to try the harder drugs first.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3600369/\&quot;\u003EAnother study\u003C/a\u003E indicated RAND&#39;s alternative explanation is more plausible than the gateway drug theory. Researchers found no conclusive evidence that marijuana use leads to harder drug use, and they concluded that the gateway drug theory wrongly treats a correlation as causation.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EMeanwhile, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/5/15/5717074/no-marijuana-isnt-a-gateway-drug\&quot;\u003Ea 2014 study\u003C/a\u003E found an uptick in marijuana use did not lead to more hard drug use. The findings, along with other research into the subject, suggest marijuana is not a gateway drug.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5324385,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-legalization-more-marijuana-use&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/marijuana-legalization-more-marijuana-use?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5324385&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Does marijuana legalization lead to more marijuana use?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EWhether full marijuana legalization leads to more marijuana use is unclear at this point. And research from places with \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-marijuana-decriminalization\&quot;\u003Emarijuana decriminalization\u003C/a\u003E and \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/what-is-medical-marijuana\&quot;\u003Emedical marijuana\u003C/a\u003E legalization has produced mixed results.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ESince only a few states and countries allow marijuana for recreational purposes, and even fewer allow the drug&#39;s widespread commercialization, there&#39;s not a lot of research on whether full legalization and sales lead more people to use the drug. The available studies instead focus on what happens after decriminalization and medical legalization, because way more states and nations have passed such laws.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E \u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana store\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;2402622\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/pnN-KdmGBnIAm9Wzx4LL4g2hgdg=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2402622/459780027.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2402622/459780027.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana store\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/pnN-KdmGBnIAm9Wzx4LL4g2hgdg=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2402622/459780027.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n \u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA marijuana dispensary prepares for the launch of recreational sales in Colorado. (RJ Sangosti / Denver Post via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://papers.nber.org/tmp/80514-w20332.pdf\&quot;\u003EA study\u003C/a\u003E from researchers at Montana State University, the University of Colorado in Denver, and the University of Oregon looked at teen pot use data between 1993 and 2011; it concluded medical marijuana legalization did not lead to more marijuana use among high school students. Similarly, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/5/15/5717074/no-marijuana-isnt-a-gateway-drug\&quot;\u003Eanother study\u003C/a\u003E from Emory University researchers found medical marijuana legalization led to more marijuana use among  adults 21 and older, but no discernible effect among teenagers.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EBut these studies didn&#39;t account for variation in medical marijuana laws — whether a state allows dispensaries that sell pot, home growing, or neither. \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/pam.21804/full\&quot;\u003EA comprehensive study\u003C/a\u003E of medical marijuana laws from researchers at the RAND Corporation found policies that allow medical marijuana dispensaries correlate with increases in overall marijuana use and dependence for adults 21 and older but only rises in dependence among youth. The findings suggest that \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/9/23/6218695/case-against-pot-legalization-big-marijuana\&quot;\u003Ethe commercialization of marijuana\u003C/a\u003E can lead to more access and use, particularly among adults.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EMeanwhile, \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167629614000356\&quot;\u003Ea study\u003C/a\u003E from researchers at the University of Melbourne and Norwegian Institute for Alcohol and Drug Research found a slight increase in marijuana use during the first five years of decriminalization in Australia, and people appeared more likely to start using marijuana at an earlier age during those five years. But after five years of decriminalization, the policy seemed to have no impact on marijuana use among youth or adults.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThis, for now, is what we know about changes in use after states and countries relax their marijuana laws. But we&#39;re still waiting to see whether full legalization, particularly the commercialization and sales of marijuana, leads to an uptick in use in places like Colorado and Washington.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5324447,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/tax-revenue-marijuana-legalization&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/tax-revenue-marijuana-legalization?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5324447&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;How much tax revenue would come from marijuana legalization?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003ENationwide marijuana legalization could produce billions in revenue for all levels of government, but the total impact would still be a small share of government budgets.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Colorado marijuana dispensary\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;679910\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/jFfj-O2Qi-5Yvc87GXOsGTSLfbs=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679910/459999023.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679910/459999023.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;Colorado marijuana dispensary\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn3.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/jFfj-O2Qi-5Yvc87GXOsGTSLfbs=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/679910/459999023.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA line stretches a Colorado marijuana dispensary during the first day of legal sales. (Joe Amon / Denver Post via Getty Images)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://object.cato.org/sites/cato.org/files/pubs/pdf/DrugProhibitionWP.pdf\&quot;\u003EA 2010 paper\u003C/a\u003E from the Cato Institute found legalizing marijuana would net all levels of the government $17.4 billion annually. Half of that would come from reduced spending, particularly for drug enforcement. The other $8.7 billion would come from taxing marijuana like alcohol and tobacco.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EWhile that sounds like a big number, the amount of government spending from municipalities, states, and the federal government is really big, too. So that $17.4 billion works out to 0.3 percent of all 2008 government spending in the United States.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EColorado became the first state to get a real-world look at the potential tax revenue, with marijuana tax receipts for the first month of full legalization \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2014/03/10/marijuana-revenue-colorado-taxes/6261131/\&quot;\u003Etotaling $3.5 million\u003C/a\u003E. Colorado Gov. John Hickenlooper&#39;s \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.colorado.gov/cs/Satellite?blobcol=urldata\u0026blobheader=application%2Fpdf\u0026blobkey=id\u0026blobtable=MungoBlobs\u0026blobwhere=1251943287907\u0026ssbinary=true\&quot;\u003EFebruary budget projection\u003C/a\u003E estimated marijuana would produce $134 million in the following fiscal year (about 0.5 percent of the state&#39;s overall budget), but, citing uncertainty in the market, his administration later \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.9news.com/story/news/politics/2014/04/08/hickenlooper-pot-tax/7434237/\&quot;\u003Erevised\u003C/a\u003E the estimate downward by more than $20 million.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5325329,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/Colorado-legalized-marijuana&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/Colorado-legalized-marijuana?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5325329&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;What&#39;s happened in Colorado and Washington since they legalized marijuana?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EColorado&#39;s experience with marijuana legalization has so far gone\u0026nbsp;\u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/12/24/7408571/marijuana-legalization-colorado\&quot;\u003Ebetter than many critics expected\u003C/a\u003E, although drug policy experts caution that the process is still in its early stages. Washington state, on the other hand, has barely gotten off the ground due to \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2015/1/16/7556975/washington-state-marijuana-legalization\&quot;\u003Ecompetition with the unregulated medical, black, and gray markets\u003C/a\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.samhsa.gov/data/sites/default/files/NSDUHStateEst2012-2013-p1/ChangeTabs/NSDUHsaeShortTermCHG2013.htm\&quot;\u003ENational Survey on Drug Use and Health\u003C/a\u003E shows past-month marijuana use increased in Colorado and Washington state among adults 18  and older — but not youth aged 12 to 17 — between a 2011-2012 period and a  2012-2013 period. But the data doesn&#39;t cover 2014, the first year of recreational sales. \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/9/23/6218695/case-against-pot-legalization-big-marijuana\&quot;\u003EThe full commercialization of marijuana\u003C/a\u003E could affect use, particularly among adolescents, in different ways.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana Washington\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;2883848\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Sb90cFZD_8CL1iBS3yij4ZKuKnc=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2883848/451852710.0.jpg\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2883848/451852710.0.jpg\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;marijuana Washington\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Sb90cFZD_8CL1iBS3yij4ZKuKnc=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/2883848/451852710.0.jpg\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp class=\&quot;caption\&quot;\u003EA customer inspects marijuana in one of Washington state&#39;s first recreational stores. (David Ryder / Getty Images News)\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.colorado.gov/cs/Satellite/Revenue-Main/XRM/1251633259746\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;\u003ERevenue from sales\u003C/a\u003E has generally trended up in Colorado throughout the year. And serious violent and property crimes in Denver, the Colorado city  with the most recreational marijuana shops, are actually \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.denvergov.org/police/PoliceDepartment/CrimeInformation/CrimeStatisticsMaps/tabid/441370/Default.aspx\&quot; target=\&quot;_blank\&quot;\u003Edown\u003C/a\u003E from 2013, despite \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/4/3/5563134/marijuana-legalization-crime-denver-colorado\&quot;\u003Ewarnings\u003C/a\u003E from law enforcement.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIn Washington state, tax revenues are coming in higher than previously projected, according to \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/20/legal-pot-washington-market-tax-revenue_n_6191848.html\&quot;\u003Ethe Associated Press\u003C/a\u003E. The industry is expected to bring in more than $694 million in state revenue through mid-2019, up from a previous projection of $636 million.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EOne major problem did emerge after the beginning of sales: \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/10/21/6995119/marijuana-legalization-pot-weed-edibles-candy-food\&quot;\u003Emarijuana edibles\u003C/a\u003E that are riskier to consume than other cannabis goods and could be inadvertently marketed to children. Several issues, including New York Times columnist \u003Ca target=\&quot;_blank\&quot; href=\&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/04/opinion/dowd-dont-harsh-our-mellow-dude.html\&quot;\u003EMaureen Dowd\u003C/a\u003E&#39;s bad experience with edibles, have spurred lawmakers and regulators to tighten rules on the pot-infused treats.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThere have also been some less prevalent concerns about a few people \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.vox.com/2014/5/6/5687174/marijuana-enthusiasts-are-blowing-themselves-up\&quot;\u003Eblowing themselves up\u003C/a\u003E while making marijuana-based hash oil. So far, officials have responded by warning pot users to not cook hash oil at home.\u003C/p\u003E&quot;},{&quot;id&quot;:5325581,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/drugged-driving&quot;,&quot;share_url&quot;:&quot;http://www.vox.com/cards/marijuana-legalization/drugged-driving?utm_campaign=vox\u0026utm_content=card-bottom\u0026utm_medium=social&quot;,&quot;short_url&quot;:&quot;http://vox.com/e/5325581&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Does marijuana affect someone&#39;s ability to drive?&quot;,&quot;status&quot;:&quot;Published&quot;,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;\u003Cp\u003EThere&#39;s still \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.denverpost.com/marijuana/ci_26446947/marijuanas-hazy-contribution-highway-deaths\&quot;\u003Ea lot of debate\u003C/a\u003E about how much marijuana affects someone&#39;s ability to drive safely and whether measuring THC, the psychoactive substance in marijuana, is the right way to evaluate the drug&#39;s effects on the road.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24411797\&quot;\u003EOne study\u003C/a\u003E from the Pacific Institute for Research and Evaluation found marijuana didn&#39;t increase a driver&#39;s chances of getting into a crash, and \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2722956/\&quot;\u003Esome research\u003C/a\u003E from Yale University found being high doesn&#39;t impair all drivers in the same way. But in \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.cuinjuryresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/Li-et-al-AAP-2013.pdf\&quot;\u003Eanother study\u003C/a\u003E, Columbia University researchers estimated that, while alcohol multiplies the chance of a fatal accident by more than 13 times, marijuana nearly doubles the risk.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cfigure class=\&quot;e-image\&quot;\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\&quot;&#39;position:relative;&#39;\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;DUI risk\&quot; class=\&quot;vox-lazy-load m-chorus-asset__in-entry-body\&quot; data-chorus-asset-id=\&quot;697164\&quot; data-full-size=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/h92Cl5054PGVmGn42JO2UK5AF1g=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/697164/DUI_risk.0.png\&quot; data-original=\&quot;https://cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/697164/DUI_risk.0.png\&quot; src=\&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==\&quot;\u003E\n      \u003Cnoscript\u003E\n        \u003Cimg alt=\&quot;DUI risk\&quot; src=\&quot;https://cdn2.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/h92Cl5054PGVmGn42JO2UK5AF1g=/cdn0.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/697164/DUI_risk.0.png\&quot;\u003E\n\u003C/noscript\u003E    \u003C/span\u003E\n\n\n\u003C/figure\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EEven if marijuana does impair some drivers, a major issue is finding the correct way to evaluate a drugged driver&#39;s level of impairment — and there&#39;s been little luck so far in finding a scientifically supported measure.\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003ELegalization advocates \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.businessinsider.com/why-dui-limits-for-pot-are-bad-2013-12\&quot;\u003Epoint out\u003C/a\u003E that THC can remain in a person&#39;s system days and even weeks after it&#39;s  consumed, and THC levels don&#39;t always correlate with level of impairment. Even  the federal government \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.nhtsa.gov/people/injury/research/job185drugs/cannabis.htm\&quot;\u003Eacknowledges\u003C/a\u003E that it&#39;s \&quot;difficult to establish a relationship between a person&#39;s THC  blood or plasma concentration and performance impairing effects.\&quot;\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EStill, both \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://www.coloradodot.info/programs/alcohol-and-impaired-driving/druggeddriving/marijuana-and-driving\&quot;\u003EColorado\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E and \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\&quot;http://lcb.wa.gov/marijuana/faqs_i-502\&quot;\u003EWashington\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E forbid drivers from having five or more nanograms of active THC per milliliter of blood. If a  driver breaches the limit, administrative and criminal penalties could  apply. (For each state&#39;s law, check out NORML&#39;s \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://norml.org/legal/drugged-driving\&quot;\u003Efull list\u003C/a\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E.)\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EBefore drivers get to sobriety checkpoints, Colorado officials hope to discourage drugged driving through an education campaign. \u003Ca href=\&quot;http://time.com/16346/the-colorado-state-government-made-these-ads-about-smoking-and-driving-and-theyre-funny-even-if-you-arent-high/\&quot;\u003ESome of the advertisements\u003C/a\u003E use a little humor to get their point across.\u0